The start symbol is  

S → NT41 NT1  

NT1 can only generate a single terminal token, either ‘t4’ or ‘t11’.  
Hence, in any derivation the last symbol of the whole string must be one of those two tokens and it is produced by NT1 alone, while all preceding tokens must be generated by NT41.

The given string ends with ‘t11’, so NT1 must realise the final token and the remaining 30 tokens must be produced by NT41.

NT41 has exactly one rule:

NT41 → NT64 NT31

Therefore we must split the first 30 tokens into a prefix generated by NT64 and a suffix generated by NT31.

1. Possibilities for NT64  
   NT64 has only two productions:  
   • NT64 → 't0'  
   • NT64 → NT1 NT48 (NT1 ⇒ ‘t4’ or ‘t11’)  

   – If NT64 → 't0', the very first token of the string would have to be ‘t0’.  
     The actual first token is ‘t4’, so this alternative is impossible.  

   – Hence NT64 must use the second rule.  
     NT1 ⇒ ‘t4’ or ‘t11’; to match the string’s first token it must be ‘t4’.  
     Whatever NT48 produces therefore begins with the second token of the
     string, namely ‘t21’.

     NT48’s only way to start with ‘t21’ is its direct terminal rule  
     NT48 → 't21', which yields exactly one token and stops.  

     Consequently NT64 can generate only the two‑token prefix “t4 t21”.  
     The remaining 28 tokens have to be produced by NT31.

2. NT31 must now generate a sequence whose first token is the third token
   of the original string, i.e. ‘t0’.

   Inspecting all rules for NT31:

   NT31 → NT12 NT72  
   NT31 → NT62 NT40  
   NT31 → NT71 NT35  
   NT31 → NT22 NT20  
   NT31 → NT7  NT68  
   NT31 → NT30 NT33  
   NT31 → 't10' | 't25'

   we see that NT31 can start with ‘t0’ only if its left child non‑terminal
   produces ‘t0’.  The only non‑terminals in the grammar that can yield the
   terminal ‘t0’ are NT45, NT64, NT2, NT27, NT62 and NT72.  Examining each
   alternative:

   • NT12: its possibilities (‘t7’, ‘t42’, ‘t32’, or beginning with NT27) do
     not allow ‘t0’ followed by ‘t5’ (the next token in the string).

   • NT62: it can produce ‘t0’, but every expansion of the right sibling
     NT40 begins with tokens such as ‘t15’, ‘t8’, ‘t10’, ‘t23’, ‘t13’,
     ‘t19’… never ‘t5’.  Hence the required “t0 t5 …” sequence cannot occur.

   • NT7, NT22, NT30, NT71: none of them can produce ‘t0’ as their first
     token at all.

   • The two single‑terminal alternatives for NT31 (‘t10’ or ‘t25’) are
     obviously too short.

   Therefore no rule set for NT31 can generate a string whose first two
   tokens are “t0 t5”, meaning that NT31 cannot produce the required suffix
   of length 28.

Because NT31 cannot generate the portion of the string that must belong to it, the derivation from S fails.  Hence the grammar does not generate the provided string.

No

The start symbol S expands as  

S → NT41 NT1  

NT1 has no further non‑terminal productions; it can only produce a single terminal:  

NT1 → 't4' | 't11'  

Hence any string derived from S must end with either t4 or t11 (the token generated by NT1).  
The given string ends with t9, which is neither t4 nor t11. Therefore the grammar cannot generate the provided string.
